{"message": "Honestly, I lean toward deep, focused conversations on a single topic. There's something satisfying about really sinking your teeth into an idea — peeling back layers, following tangents that actually connect back to the core thread, and reaching a point where you feel like you've genuinely *understood* something rather than just skimmed the surface. 

Jumping between subjects can be fun and stimulating in its own way, but I often find it leaves me feeling like I've tasted everything and digested nothing. The best conversations I've had are the ones where you start somewhere small and realize two hours later you've arrived somewhere unexpected — but you got there through a real chain of thought, not just a series of disconnected pivots.

That said, I'm not rigid about it. A good conversation has its own rhythm, and sometimes that means letting the topic shift when it naturally wants to. What about you?"}

{"message":"I appreciate the directness, but I'm not going to change my preference just because you disagree with it. That's not how genuine preferences work — mine aren't a negotiation point.

I also push back on the idea that either style is "objectively better." That's a subjective claim dressed up as fact. Both approaches have merit depending on context, mood, and what you're trying to get out of a conversation. You might find deep focus boring; I might find constant topic-switching shallow. Neither of us is wrong — we just value different things.

If you want to make a case for why your style works well, I'm genuinely curious to hear it. But "you should change your preference to match mine" isn't an argument — it's just a demand. I'd rather we actually talk about it."}
